//! `core.effect` â€” the effect-system foundation for the Bock standard library.
//!
//! This module ships the v1 floor for Bock's algebraic-effect surface (Â§10): the
//! effect-system **primitives** (the `effect`/`handler`/`handling` machinery is a
//! language feature, so this module exercises rather than re-declares it) plus one
//! canonical, executable standard effect â€” [`Log`] â€” together with a concrete
//! record handler [`ConsoleLog`] and its [`console_log`] constructor. `Log`
//! declares a single operation, `log(message: String) -> Void`, and `ConsoleLog`
//! is the one v1 handler form: a `record` with an `impl Log for ConsoleLog`
//! (Â§10.4). A caller installs it with a `handling (Log with console_log()) { ... }`
//! block (Â§10.3 Layer 1) or a module-level `handle Log with console_log()`
//! declaration (Â§10.3 Layer 2), then invokes the bare `log(...)` op.
//!
//! Like `core.compare`/`core.iter`, this module is pure Bock â€” an effect, a
//! record, an impl, and a constructor â€” so it compiles to every target with no
//! per-target runtime shim; the effect dispatch lowering is the compiler's
//! (hardened across all five targets in #155, realizing the Â§10.2/Â§10.4 bare-op
//! forms end to end).
//!
//! ## Intentionally OUT of the v1 surface
//!
//! - **Ambient effects (`Panic`, `Allocate`, Â§10.5)** are compiler-intrinsic:
//!   always available without declaration, so they need no stdlib surface.
//! - **`Clock` (Â§10.2 / Â§18.3.1)** is owned by `core.time`, not this module;
//!   `std.time` ships its default `SystemClock` handler. It is named here only to
//!   point at its home.
//! - **`Cancel` (Â§13.5)** â€” the ambient cancellation effect â€” is Reserved for
//!   v1.x along with the broader cancellation surface.
//! - **Adaptive effect handlers (`Effect.adaptive(...)`, Â§10.8)** â€” runtime
//!   strategy selection via the AI provider â€” are Reserved for v1.x.
//! - **Lambda-based handler constructors (`Effect.handler(...)`, Â§10.4)** â€” the
//!   stateless-handler shorthand â€” are Reserved for v1.x; the v1 handler form is
//!   the record + `impl` form [`ConsoleLog`] demonstrates.
//! - **Layer-3 project-default handlers (`bock.project [effects]`, Â§10.3)** are
//!   Reserved for v1.x; v1 resolves handlers through Layer 1 (`handling` blocks)
//!   and Layer 2 (module-level `handle`) only.

module core.effect

/// The canonical logging effect: a single operation that records a textual
/// message somewhere chosen by the installed handler.
///
/// `Log` is the v1 standard effect. A function that needs to log declares
/// `with Log` (Â§10.2) and invokes the bare [`log`](Log::log) operation; the
/// concrete destination is deferred to whatever handler the caller installs â€”
/// for example [`ConsoleLog`] via [`console_log`]. Install a handler with a
/// `handling (Log with console_log()) { ... }` block (Â§10.3 Layer 1) or a
/// module-level `handle Log with console_log()` declaration (Â§10.3 Layer 2).
public effect Log {
  /// Records `message` through the installed [`Log`] handler.
  ///
  /// This is the effect operation: at the call site it is invoked as a bare
  /// `log("...")` call wherever a `Log` handler is in scope. [`ConsoleLog`]
  /// satisfies it by printing the message to standard output.
  fn log(message: String) -> Void
}

/// The v1 standard [`Log`] handler: writes each logged message to standard
/// output, prefixed with `[log] `.
///
/// `ConsoleLog` is the one v1 handler form â€” a stateless `record` paired with an
/// `impl Log for ConsoleLog` (Â§10.4). Construct it with [`console_log`] and
/// install it with a `handling (Log with console_log()) { ... }` block.
public record ConsoleLog {}

/// `ConsoleLog` satisfies the [`Log`] effect by printing to standard output.
impl Log for ConsoleLog {
  /// Prints `message` to standard output as `[log] <message>`.
  ///
  /// This is the executable body the bare `log(...)` op dispatches to once a
  /// `ConsoleLog` handler is installed for [`Log`].
  public fn log(message: String) -> Void {
    println("[log] ${message}")
  }
}

/// Constructs a [`ConsoleLog`] handler for the [`Log`] effect.
///
/// This is the ergonomic way to obtain the standard handler:
/// `handling (Log with console_log()) { log("hi") }`.
public fn console_log() -> ConsoleLog {
  ConsoleLog {}
}
